  "Running two exergonic reactions simultaneously": "",
  "Storing all cellular energy as heat": "",
  "Using energy from an exergonic reaction to drive an endergonic reaction": "",
  "Preventing entropy from increasing": "",
  "Energy coupling links an exergonic reaction (like ATP hydrolysis) to an endergonic reaction (like protein synthesis), allowing the cell to perform work. ATP serves as the intermediary between these reactions.": "",
  "What happens to the free energy of a system at equilibrium?": "",
  "Free energy oscillates between positive and negative values": "",
  "Free energy increases continuously": "",
  "Free energy is at its maximum": "",
  "Free energy is at its minimum and no net work can be done (ΔG = 0)": "",
  "At equilibrium, ΔG = 0 and the system can do no net work. Living cells avoid equilibrium by continuously importing nutrients and exporting waste, maintaining a steady state far from equilibrium.": "",
