  "What is metabolism?": "",
  "The totality of an organism's chemical reactions, including both catabolic (breakdown) and anabolic (synthesis) pathways": "",
  "The transport of molecules across cell membranes": "",
  "The rate at which an organism grows": "",
  "Only the breakdown of food molecules for energy": "",
  "Metabolism encompasses all chemical reactions in an organism. Catabolic pathways release energy by breaking down molecules; anabolic pathways consume energy to build complex molecules. Together they maintain life.": "",
  "What does 'entropy' mean?": "",
  "The speed of a chemical reaction, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual entropy mechanisms at work": "",
  "A measure of the disorder or randomness in a system; the second law of thermodynamics states that the total entropy of the universe always increases": "",
  "The number of products formed in a reaction regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "The total amount of energy in the universe under most circumstances involving entropy": "",
  "Entropy (S) is a measure of disorder or randomness. Living organisms maintain low internal entropy (high order) by increasing entropy in their surroundings, consistent with the second law of thermodynamics.": "",
  "What is an 'exergonic reaction'?": "",
  "A reaction that requires energy input to proceed": "",
  "A reaction that produces no products": "",
  "A reaction that only occurs at high temperatures": "",
  "A chemical reaction that releases free energy (ΔG < 0), proceeding spontaneously from reactants to products": "",
  "Exergonic reactions release free energy (negative ΔG) and are thermodynamically spontaneous. However, 'spontaneous' does not mean 'fast'—many exergonic reactions still require activation energy to begin.": "",
  "What does 'endergonic reaction' mean?": "",
  "A chemical reaction that absorbs free energy from its surroundings (ΔG > 0), requiring energy input to proceed": "",
  "A reaction that produces entropy": "",
  "A reaction that releases heat into the environment": "",
  "A reaction that occurs only in endocrine cells": "",
  "Endergonic reactions have a positive ΔG, meaning they require an input of free energy. Products have more free energy than reactants. In cells, endergonic reactions are driven by coupling to exergonic reactions like ATP hydrolysis.": "",
  "What is 'activation energy'?": "",
  "The energy needed to break ATP into ADP": "",
  "The energy stored in the products of a reaction": "",
  "The minimum amount of energy required to start a chemical reaction by bringing reactants to the transition state": "",
  "The total energy released during a reaction": "",
  "Activation energy (Ea) is the energy barrier that must be overcome for a reaction to proceed. Enzymes lower Ea by stabilizing the transition state, dramatically increasing reaction rates without changing the overall ΔG.": "",
  "What does 'catabolism' mean?": "",
  "The movement of molecules across membranes": "",
  "The process of cell division": "",
  "Metabolic pathways that build complex molecules from simpler ones": "",
  "Metabolic pathways that break down complex molecules into simpler ones, releasing energy (exergonic)": "",
  "Catabolism is the set of metabolic pathways that break down complex molecules (proteins, carbohydrates, lipids) into simpler components, releasing stored energy. Cellular respiration is a major catabolic pathway.": "",
  "What is 'anabolism'?": "",
  "The production of heat during exercise": "",
  "Metabolic pathways that synthesize complex molecules from simpler precursors, requiring energy input (endergonic)": "",
  "The recycling of ATP to ADP": "",
  "The breakdown of food molecules in the digestive system": "",
  "Anabolism is the constructive branch of metabolism that builds complex molecules (proteins, nucleic acids, polysaccharides) from smaller precursors. Anabolic reactions consume energy, often supplied by ATP.": "",
  "What does 'thermodynamics' refer to in biology?": "",
  "The process of converting heat into mechanical work": "",
  "The study of energy transformations that occur in living organisms and the physical universe, governed by the laws of energy conservation and entropy": "",
  "The study of temperature regulation in warm-blooded animals": "",
  "The measurement of metabolic rate using calorimeters": "",
  "Thermodynamics in biology examines how energy flows through living systems. The first law (energy conservation) and second law (entropy increase) govern all metabolic processes, from photosynthesis to respiration.": "",
  "What is 'phosphorylation'?": "",
  "The removal of phosphate from a molecule when the interaction between phosphorylation and activity factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The synthesis of phospholipids for membranes when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The bonding of phosphorus atoms in DNA, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these phosphorylation dynamics operate": "",
  "The transfer of a phosphate group to a molecule, often changing its shape and activity; a common mechanism for energy transfer and regulation in cells": "",
  "Phosphorylation adds a phosphate group (from ATP) to a protein or other molecule, changing its conformation and activity. Kinase enzymes catalyze phosphorylation, which regulates many cellular processes.": "",
  "What does 'energy coupling' mean?": "",
  "The use of energy released from an exergonic reaction to drive an endergonic reaction, typically through ATP as an intermediary": "",
  "The conversion of all energy into heat, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "The pairing of two identical energy molecules according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The storage of energy in lipid molecules, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Energy coupling connects exergonic and endergonic reactions so that the energy released by one drives the other. ATP serves as the shuttle, being produced by exergonic catabolic reactions and consumed by endergonic anabolic reactions.": "",
  "A student places a sugar cube in a dish and observes that it does not spontaneously combust, even though the reaction C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O is highly exergonic (ΔG = -2,870 kJ/mol). Why doesn't the sugar burn spontaneously?": "",
  "The reaction is actually endergonic at room temperature, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Sugar cannot react with oxygen considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "The entropy change prevents the reaction from occurring in most scenarios involving barrier factors": "",
  "Although the reaction is exergonic, it requires activation energy to begin; the sugar needs an initial input (like a spark) to reach the transition state": "",
  "Even though glucose combustion has a large negative ΔG, it has a high activation energy barrier. Without enough energy to reach the transition state (e.g., from a match), the stable covalent bonds in glucose resist breaking. Enzymes in cells lower this barrier.": "",
  "A biologist calculates that a typical human cell uses approximately 10 million ATP molecules per second and recycles its entire pool of ATP roughly every 1-2 minutes. What does this rapid ATP turnover tell us about how cells manage energy?": "",
