  "Cells can function without ATP for extended periods when the interaction between cell and human factors is taken into full account": "",
  "ATP is not stored in large quantities but is continuously regenerated from ADP + Pi in a rapid cycle; the cell maintains a steady state of ATP production and consumption far from equilibrium": "",
  "Cells maintain only a small pool of ATP that is rapidly cycled between ATP and ADP. A human body recycles its weight in ATP each day. This continuous turnover keeps the cell far from equilibrium, enabling work.": "",
  "A nutritionist explains to a client that a gram of fat provides 9 kcal of energy while a gram of carbohydrate provides only 4 kcal. Using thermodynamic principles, why do fats store more energy per gram?": "",
  "Fats are denser than carbohydrates because both theoretical frameworks and empirical evidence suggest that kcal outcomes follow consistent trajectories": "",
  "Fats are digested faster than carbohydrates, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual kcal mechanisms at work": "",
  "Fat molecules have a higher proportion of C-H bonds (which are energy-rich and highly reduced), so their complete oxidation releases more free energy than the more oxidized C-O bonds in carbohydrates": "",
  "Carbohydrates contain more water, which dilutes their energy content, as conventional kcal theory would suggest": "",
  "Fat molecules are highly reduced (many C-H bonds, few C-O bonds), meaning they have more electrons to donate to the ETC when oxidized. Complete oxidation of these reduced bonds releases approximately 9 kcal/g, compared to 4 kcal/g for carbohydrates.": "",
  "A scientist studying extremophiles discovers bacteria living near deep-sea hydrothermal vents where no sunlight penetrates. These bacteria derive energy from oxidizing hydrogen sulfide (H₂S). How does this relate to the laws of thermodynamics?": "",
  "Chemosynthetic bacteria use the exergonic oxidation of H₂S as their energy source instead of sunlight, converting chemical energy to ATP while still obeying both laws of thermodynamics": "",
