  "A student observes that fireflies produce bioluminescence. She learns that the enzyme luciferase catalyzes the oxidation of luciferin using ATP and O₂, releasing light. Using energy concepts, how does a firefly convert chemical energy to light?": "",
  "Fireflies generate electricity that produces sparks due to the well-established relationship between energy trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Heat from metabolism causes chemicals to glow, since the relevant energy factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "ATP hydrolysis provides activation energy for the exergonic oxidation of luciferin; the released free energy excites the product molecule, which emits a photon of visible light as it returns to ground state": "",
  "The firefly absorbs sunlight during the day and re-emits it at night, since standard models of energy behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Bioluminescence demonstrates energy transformation: chemical bond energy (ATP + luciferin) → excited electronic state → light energy (photon). This is a remarkably efficient process (~90% of energy as light, only ~10% as heat).": "",
  "A sports physiologist measures that a sprinter's muscles produce approximately 500 watts of power during a 100-meter dash, but only about 125 watts appears as mechanical work (movement). Where does the remaining 375 watts go?": "",
